'''''The Return of Heracles''''' is a [[role-playing video game]] for the [[Atari 8-bit computers]], [[Commodore 64]] and [[Apple II]]. It was written by Stuart Smith and published by [[Quality Software]] in 1983.<ref name="mania">{{cite web |title=The Return of Heracles |url=http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-400-800-xl-xe-return-of-heracles-_4355.html |website=Atari Mania}}</ref> Following Smith's adventure role playing games ''Fracas''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mocagh.org/loadpage.php?getgame=fracas-alt|title = Computer Game Museum Display Case - Fracas}}</ref> and ''[[Ali Baba and the Forty Thieves (video game)|Ali Baba and the Forty Thieves]]'', and built on an engine that was a precursor to ''[[Adventure Construction Set]]'', ''The Return of Heracles'' is set in the age of [[Greek myth]] and allows the player to assume the role of one or more heroes and attempt various quests.

It was later bundled with ''Ali Baba and the Forty Thieves'' in a compilation called ''Age of Adventure'', published by [[Electronic Arts]].

==Gameplay==
''The Return of Heracles'' is an [[Role-playing video game|RPG]] adventure. Each character is defined by three basic characteristics: strength, dexterity, and speed. Strength and dexterity determine how effective a character is in combat, while speed determines how many squares can be moved in one turn.  Characters may also have special training in defensive techniques, use of the sword, and use of the dagger.{{cn|date=October 2018}}

